<subSubSection id="C30EB4BB83777E08A3C0FD01B40D6ED0" pageId="1" pageNumber="212" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BABE73083777E08A3C0FD01B40D6ED0" blockId="1.[151,1437,664,1195]" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis id="B9603B2283777E08A3C0FD01B72F6FCC" bold="true" box="[151,274,664,690]" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C149CB383777E08A240FD01B7926FCC" authorityName="Fieber" authorityYear="1860" baseAuthorityName="Fieber" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[279,431,664,690]" class="Insecta" family="Alydidae" genus="Megalotomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9603B2283777E08A240FD01B7926FCC" box="[279,431,664,690]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">Megalotomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from other genera of the family 
<taxonomicName id="4C149CB383777E08A034FD01B5F76FCC" authorityName="Amyot &amp; Serville" authorityYear="1843" box="[867,970,664,690]" class="Insecta" family="Alydidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Alydidae</taxonomicName>
by the combination of the following characters: body slender, small to large sized, body length range 10.0–17.0 mm, body colour from yellow to black; head almost triangular, slightly narrower than pronotum; antennal segment I longer than or equal length to segment II; posterior angles of pronotum prominent, slightly raised, always pointed; femur and tibiae straight with no curving, tibiae longer than femur, femora with 3–8 spines, inner surface with plectrum; genital capsule with a pair of surcapsular spines, never crossing over, parameres elongate, slender and curved; posterior margin of female abdominal sternite VII split longitudinally in middle [valid only if specimens of female 
<taxonomicName id="4C149CB383777E08A757FCE9B6E56ED1" authority="(Say, 1825)" baseAuthorityName="Say" baseAuthorityYear="1825" class="Insecta" family="Alydidae" genus="Megalotomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quinquespinosus">
<emphasis id="B9603B2283777E08A757FCE9B3616EF4" box="[1024,1372,880,906]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">Megalotomus quinquespinosus</emphasis>
(Say, 1825)
</taxonomicName>
are examined and confirmed].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30EB4BB83777E08A390FC21B58569D4" pageId="1" pageNumber="212" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BABE73083777E08A390FC21B58569D4" blockId="1.[151,1437,664,1195]" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">
<emphasis id="B9603B2283777E08A390FC21B43C6EAC" bold="true" box="[199,513,952,978]" pageId="1" pageNumber="212">Distribution and diversity.</emphasis>
This genus is distributed in the Palaearctic and Nearctic Regions, and according to the literature (
<bibRefCitation id="EF859AC183777E08A265FC45B7F76E89" author="Dolling, W. R." box="[306,458,988,1015]" pageId="1" pageNumber="212" pagination="1843" refId="ref8309" refString="Dolling, W. R. (2006) Family Alydidae Amyot &amp; Serville, 1843. In: Aukema, B. &amp; Rieger, C. (Eds.), Catalogue of the Heteroptera of the Palaearctic Region. Vol. 5. Pentatomomorpha II. The Netherlands Entomological Society, Amsterdam, pp. 34 - 38." type="book chapter" year="2006">Dolling 2006</bibRefCitation>
) and the results presented herein contains eight species: 
<taxonomicName id="4C149CB383777E08A76BFC45B6E66965" authority="(Scopoli, 1763)" baseAuthorityName="Scopoli" baseAuthorityYear="1763" class="Insecta" family="Alydidae" genus="Megalotomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="212" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="junceus">
